<span class="author">Iwein Fuld</span>
</div>
 <div class="meta-data--item">
<div class="meta-data--icon icon blog-icon calendar"></div>
<time class="date" pubdate="" datetime="2008-02-19 11:23:00.0">February 19, 2008</time>
</div>
<div class="meta-data--item">
<div class="meta-data--icon icon blog-icon comments"></div>
<a class="comments" data-disqus-identifier="137" href="/blog/2008/02/19/enabling-test-driven-development-in-gwt-client-code#disqus_thread">
</a></div>
</header>
<section class="blog--post desktop-only">
<div><p>In the past months I’ve been working with various clients on projects using Google Web Toolkit [GWT]. I like GWT primarily because of the Java to javascript compiler. This is the key to the door letting mere mortal Java developers create RIA’s without having to learn a new language.</p>
<p>I’ve allways been a fan of test driven development, and to my disappointment at first sight it looked like TDD and GWT were not going to play together.</p>
<p>Testing GWT code is a bit problematic. The core of the problem is that GWT code is compiled to javascript before it is run. In many cases a GWT.create() statement is used to hook into the dynamic binding mechanism. When executed in normal Java environment this statement causes an exception.</p>
</div>
</section>
<a class="blog-preview--readmore desktop-only" href="/blog/2008/02/19/enabling-test-driven-development-in-gwt-client-code">
Read more...
</a>
</article>
